The isothermal compressibility of mercury is $\kappa = 26 \times 10^{−12}~$Pa$^{-1}$. At standard conditions, the pressure is $p = p_0 = 0.1~$MPa and the temperature is $T = 300~$K. By using the ideal gas law, the ratio of the molar volume $V$ to the saturated vapor pressure $V_\text{sat}$ can be expressed as $V/V_{\rm sat} = (p/p_{\rm 0})^{1/3}$. Therefore, the variation of molar mass with pressure can be calculated as
\begin{equation}
\frac{m}{m_0} = \frac{V}{V_{\text{Sat}}} = \left(\frac{p}{p_{0}}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}.
\label{eq:molar_mass_ratio} 
\end{equation}\par

Substituting the value of $\kappa$ into the equation of state of an ideal gas, $pV = nRT$, where $n$ is the number of moles, we can calculate the ratio $n/n_{0}$. Then, by using equation \eqref{eq_mass}, the variation in molar density can be obtained as $\rho = \rho_0 + \frac{\kappa}{n} \left(n - n_0\right)$. Finally, the change in mass per unit volume can be written as $\frac{\partial \rho}{\partial p}$.
